k/subprocess or model output quality is part of this behavior text.","test_description":"Given a document exceeding budget, call request-construction path with configured policy and assert resulting action is exactly truncate or reject per config, and that computed/requested token count does not exceed budget at construction time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This requires a real provider call and provider-reported usage; stubs can miss real tokenizer/model-accounting behavior. Per rule, execution through a real AI/ML API call defaults to Agentic unless exclusively infrastructure-only; here correctness is about provider model usage numbers, so Agentic remains.","test_description":"Send a representative document to the real provider through the module, capture provider-reported token usage from the response/metadata, and assert reported total is <= configured budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.68,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is orchestration/retry behavior across classifier and API-client error handling, testable with a stubbed client returning rate-limit then success. System is disqualified by behavior text because it does not require validating real network timing/OS primitives; LLM output quality is not involved, so Agentic/Workflow are not required.","test_description":"Use a fake API client scripted to return rate-limit error on first call and success on second; assert 